{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778271442,"nonce":"h+X80xIEpGc2FAW0hXjicThdf2U=","message":"**Cost-schedule confirmed analytically load-bearing for Δv \u003e 0 (see \\`6ec6b19\\` for full disposition).**\n\nC\u0026S analytical audit (\\`/tmp/flavor_ab_review/findings/cs_alignment_audit.md\\`) showed (t/N)^6 schedule + matched horizon (60 steps) account for ~−4% of the +6% gap between rlrmp first-pass replication (+2.12%) and MATLAB-faithful port (+8.24%).\n\n**Implication for any future inter-condition Δv comparison.** rlrmp training currently uses uniform / hold-cost on 1.3 s horizon. Under this loss the trained controller has no terminal cliff to fear → no incentive to rush to target → empirical Δv ≈ 0 may be **cost-function-induced** (not eliciting Δv \u003e 0 in principle, regardless of architecture) rather than **architecture-induced** (RNN-as-tracker decoupling).\n\n**Action item for future training-method work:** when revisiting Δv-based comparisons across training methods (post \\`efc4d68\\` smoothness fix for replicate variance), pair them with a cost-schedule sweep (\\`6ec6b19\\`) so cost-effects and architecture-effects can be disambiguated. The decoupling decomposition \\`8fcb6c7\\` similarly needs this controlled for — its predictions assume controllers are operating in a regime where Δv \u003e 0 is reachable.\n\nStatus: documented for record; not promoted to immediate action. Awaits \\`6ec6b19\\` running.","files":null}]}